<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-231-354  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 231 354.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 21 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bellcore announces Hypermedia tool. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bellcore Bell Communications Research Inc. (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Computer software industryProduct IntroductionData base management systemsSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BELLCORE ANNOUNCES HYPERMEDIA TOOL LIVINGSTON, NEW JERSEY, U.S.A., 1989 NOV16 (NB) -- Bellcore announced SuperBook, which could become the text end oftomorrow's Hypermedia tools.andP;  SuperBook is a prototype for a computerizeddocument-browser or text information retrieval program that can automaticallyprocess and display virtually any document that is in machine-readable form.andM;It was first developed by Pacific Bell for use in answering customers'service questions, replacing use of printed manuals and documents.andP;  Inaddition, SuperBook is also helping Bellcore understand how widespread use ofelectronic retrieval services would impact public telephone networks.andO;Bellcore is talking about licensing the underlying technology to variouscolleges, universities, library systems and other organizations.andM;SuperBook uses full-context indexing, which references every place a word isused.andP;  When a person searches for a word, SuperBook shows how many times thatword appears in each section listed in the table of contents.andP;  In addition,the system gives users the ability to create their own synonyms for termsused by the author and to add notes (which are then automatically indexed)and &quot;bookmarks.&quot;andM;Bellcore has been fine tuning a new feature for SuperBook which allows peopleto look for whole paragraphs or even entire documents that are similar inmeaning, in addition to individual words or phrases.andP;  &quot;You just giveSuperBook a sample paragraph of what you are looking for and you get back alist of items that are like your example,&quot; said co-inventor Thomas Landauer.andO;&quot;You do not have to think of words or logical queries to define what youwant.&quot;andM;SuperBook also has a &quot;dynamic&quot; table of contents, which displays headingsthat change as a user browses the text.andP;  &quot;One of the big problems people haveis getting lost in an electronic text,&quot; said Landauer.andP;  &quot;With SuperBook, youcannot get lost, you always know where you are.&quot; According to Landauer,SuperBook is effective because of the particular way its features arecombined and executed.andP;  The system was made even easier to use by observingpeople as they worked with it.andM;Recent Bellcore studies show that SuperBook improves the speed and accuracyof finding information by 25 percent compared with printed manuals.andP;  Studentswrote better essays, Landauer said, and were more eager to study texts inSuperBook form.andM;Many aspects of SuperBook aren't new, such as its inverted index retrieval,although the menu overlays may well be brand-new.andP;  Generally database sizeinterferes with searching ability as when you get millions of small recordsor thousands of big ones.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19891117/Press Contact: Deanna Munoz, BellCore,201-740-6110)</TEXT></DOC>